							<td>Published rate card, transparent pricing, furniture assembly</td>
							<td>Pricing clarity maps well to Rendin's brand values</td>
							<td><span class="badge badge-hi">High</span></td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td><strong>Sealt Siia OÜ</strong></td>
							<td>Tallinn</td>
							<td>International moves, strong Google reviews, fast turnaround</td>
							<td>Strong fit for Rendin's expat tenant segment specifically</td>
							<td><span class="badge badge-md">Medium</span></td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td><strong>Adduco / MoveMaster</strong></td>
							<td>Tallinn + Tartu</td>
							<td>FIDI/IAM accredited, international network, 30+ year track record</td>
							<td>Good for a premium tier — justifies a higher referral rate</td>
							<td><span class="badge badge-md">Medium</span></td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td><strong>FidsTrans</strong></td>
							<td>Tallinn / Harju</td>
							<td>Budget-friendly, competitive pricing, local reach</td>
							<td>Broadens addressable audience for price-sensitive tenants</td>
							<td><span class="badge badge-lo">Secondary</span></td>
						</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>

				<h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin: 36px 0 8px; color: var(--text);">Revenue model options</h3>
				<p style="margin-bottom: 24px;">Three complementary levers — each independent, all stackable. Option A is the most structurally interesting: it mirrors Rendin's own founding idea of replacing a large upfront cost with a small monthly payment — applied now to the cost of moving itself.</p>

				<div class="rev-card" style="display: block; border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);">
					<div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: flex-start; gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 14px;">
						<h4 style="margin: 0;">Option A — Moving Cost Paid in Installments</h4>
						<span style="font-family: 'Trebuchet MS', sans-serif; font-size: 0.7rem; color: var(--accent-strong); letter-spacing: 0.06em; white-space: nowrap; flex-shrink: 0; padding-top: 3px;">RECOMMENDED</span>
					</div>
					<p>When a tenant opts in, they don't pay the mover upfront. Instead, the full moving cost — say <strong>€200 for a standard local move</strong> — is spread into monthly installments of <strong>€17/month for 12 months</strong>, added to their existing Rendin invoice. Rendin pays the moving company directly, then recovers the cost gradually from the tenant over the tenancy.</p>
					<p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--muted);">This mirrors Rendin's own founding logic: replace a large upfront cost with a small monthly line. No lump-sum moving bill. No deposit. The tenant starts their tenancy with zero financial shock. Rendin charges a 10% coordination spread — it collects €220 total (€18.33/month) and pays the mover €200 — earning €20 net per tenant over the tenancy.</p>

					<div style="margin-top: 24px;">
						<p style="font-family: 'Trebuchet MS', sans-serif; font-size: 0.7rem; color: var(--muted); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 12px;">How the cash flow builds month by month — Estonia only</p>
						<table class="partner-table" style="margin: 0;">
							<thead>
								<tr>
									<th>Month</th>
									<th>New opt-ins</th>
									<th>Total active tenants paying</th>
									<th style="text-align: right;">Monthly collection</th>
									<th style="text-align: right;">Rendin net margin (10%)</th>
								</tr>
							</thead>
							<tbody>
								<tr>
									<td><strong>Month 1</strong></td>
									<td>95</td>
									<td>95</td>
									<td style="text-align: right;">€1,615</td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: rgba(20,100,60,0.85);">€162</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td><strong>Month 2</strong></td>
									<td>95 more</td>
									<td>190</td>
									<td style="text-align: right;">€3,230</td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: rgba(20,100,60,0.85);">€323</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td><strong>Month 3</strong></td>
									<td>95 more</td>
									<td>285</td>
									<td style="text-align: right;">€4,845</td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: rgba(20,100,60,0.85);">€485</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td style="color: var(--muted);" colspan="2">Month 4–11</td>
									<td style="color: var(--muted);">380 → 1,045</td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: var(--muted);">€6,460 → €17,765</td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: var(--muted);">€646 → €1,777</td>
								</tr>
								<tr style="background: var(--text);">
									<td style="color: #f4efe7;"><strong>Month 12</strong></td>
									<td style="color: rgba(244,239,231,0.55);">95 more</td>
									<td style="color: rgba(244,239,231,0.55);">1,140 tenants</td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: #f4efe7;">€19,380</td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: #6fcf97;">€1,938</td>
								</tr>
								<tr style="background: var(--panel-strong);">
									<td colspan="3"><strong>Year 1 total collected</strong></td>
									<td style="text-align: right;"><strong>€125,970</strong></td>
									<td style="text-align: right; color: rgba(20,100,60,0.85);"><strong>~€12,600</strong></td>
								</tr>
							</tbody>
						</table>
						<p style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 10px;">The €125,970 collected is mostly pass-through — Rendin is disbursing it to movers. The €12,600 is Rendin's actual net margin after paying movers, based on a 10% spread. Month 1 feels small — €162 — but the model requires no additional effort to grow. Every new cohort adds to the base automatically.</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="rev-card">
					<div>
						<h4>Option B — Referral Commission from Moving Partner</h4>
						<p>In parallel, Rendin earns 10–12% of the booked move value from the moving company — paid by the partner, not the tenant. The tenant pays nothing extra. The moving company benefits from a warm, high-intent lead with move-in date and address already known, making the commission straightforward to justify to partners.</p>
						<p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--muted);">On an average €250 move, this is ~€25–30 per booking. At 95 bookings/month (Estonia), that's roughly €2,600/month. Unlike Option A this does not compound — it resets each month based on new bookings only.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="rev-est">
						<span class="amount">~€31k</span>
						<span class="freq">year 1 · Estonia</span>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="rev-card">
					<div>
						<h4>Option C — Partner Placement Fee (Phase 2)</h4>
						<p>Once the feature has 3–6 months of conversion data, Rendin can offer moving companies a paid "priority slot" — appearing first in the recommendation widget for a flat monthly fee of €200–400. This is a separate, additive stream that doesn't affect the installment or commission models. Introduced only after proving value to partners.</p>
						<p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--muted);">Organic ranking still exists — a paying partner still has to meet the vetting criteria. The placement fee buys visibility, not a pass on quality.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="rev-est">
						<span class="amount">~€8k</span>
						<span class="freq">year 1 · 2 partners</span>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="callout" style="background: var(--text); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);">
					<p class="callout-label" style="color: var(--accent);">Combined revenue picture — Estonia, year 1</p>
					<p style="color: rgba(244,239,231,0.65);">Option A generates <strong style="color: #f4efe7;">~€12,600 net margin</strong> over year 1 from the 10% coordination spread — small in month 1 (€162), growing to €1,938/month by month 12 as cohorts accumulate. Option B adds ~€31k from partner commissions. Option C adds ~€7.2k from placement fees. <strong style="color: #f4efe7;">Combined net to Rendin: ~€51k in year 1</strong> — from a feature with no trucks, no staff, and no new insurance exposure. At Poland scale (year 2, ~2,000 contracts/month), the same model projects to <strong style="color: #f4efe7;">€200k+/year</strong>.</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<!-- 06 Metrics & Risks -->
			<section class="section cs-section panel" id="metrics">
				<p class="cs-section-num">06 — Metrics & Risks</p>
				<h2>How to know<br><em>if it's working</em></h2>

				<div class="metric-grid">
					<div class="metric-item">
						<h4>North Star</h4>
						<ul>
							<li>
								Moving feature conversion rate — target ≥30%
								<span class="metric-explain">Of every 100 tenants who see the "Plan your move" prompt, at least 30 should go on to book a mover through it. This is the headline number that proves the feature is worth keeping.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								Post-move satisfaction vs. tenants who didn't use the feature
								<span class="metric-explain">Both groups are asked "would you recommend Rendin?" after move-in. If tenants who used the moving feature score higher, it means it genuinely improved how they feel about Rendin — not just the move itself.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								Monthly referral income vs. goal
								<span class="metric-explain">Is the commission earned from moving bookings hitting the monthly target? If not, something in the funnel needs fixing.</span>
							</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
					<div class="metric-item">
						<h4>Product Health</h4>
						<ul>
							<li>
								How many tenants click the moving prompt
								<span class="metric-explain">After signing, a card appears saying "Need help moving?" — what share of tenants actually tap it? A very low rate means the message or placement is wrong, before anything else is evaluated.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								How many complete the quote request form
								<span class="metric-explain">Of the people who clicked, how many filled in the form and hit submit? A big drop here usually means the form asks for too much, or information people don't have to hand.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								Where in the booking process people abandon
								<span class="metric-explain">There are several steps: click → fill form → pick a mover → confirm. Knowing the exact step where most people leave tells you what to fix — rather than guessing.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								Whether the moving feature leads to faster, cleaner move-ins
								<span class="metric-explain">Rendin has a digital move-in checklist both parties complete together. Do tenants who used a vetted mover complete it more often? If yes, a smoother move correlates with better documentation — which protects both sides if there's a later dispute.</span>
							</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
					<div class="metric-item">
						<h4>Business Health</h4>
						<ul>
							<li>
								Partner quality over time
								<span class="metric-explain">Each year, Rendin re-checks its moving partners — do they still meet the required rating, insurance, and service standards? A declining pass rate is an early warning that quality is slipping before tenants start complaining.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								Whether partners pay their referral fees reliably
								<span class="metric-explain">If a moving company consistently pays late or not at all, it signals either cash flow problems or that the partner doesn't value the arrangement. A canary metric before bigger issues surface.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								Tenant complaints about referred movers
								<span class="metric-explain">How many tenants come back to Rendin saying "the mover you recommended was terrible"? Even one or two unresolved complaints can damage trust disproportionately — so this has a hard cap, not just a percentage threshold.</span>
							</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
					<div class="metric-item">
						<h4>Insurance Impact</h4>
						<ul>
							<li>
								Do vetted-mover tenants file fewer damage claims?
								<span class="metric-explain">Rendin's core business is covering tenant-caused damage. If tenants who used a Rendin-referred mover cause less damage during move-in, that's a direct financial argument for the feature — it reduces Rendin's own payout exposure.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								How often move-in inspections lead to disagreements
								<span class="metric-explain">When both parties walk through the apartment at move-in and sign off on its condition, "who caused that scratch" disputes become much easier to resolve. A lower dispute rate after launch suggests smoother handovers.</span>
							</li>
							<li>
								How quickly both parties sign off on move-in condition
								<span class="metric-explain">The faster landlord and tenant complete the digital inspection checklist after moving day, the less ambiguity there is about the apartment's state. Delays often mean one party is already uncomfortable — which tends to predict a claim later.</span>
							</li>
						</ul>
					</div>
				</div>

				<h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin: 36px 0 16px; color: var(--text);">Risks</h3>

				<div>
					<div class="risk-item" style="flex-direction: column; align-items: stretch; gap: 14px;">
						<div style="display: flex; gap: 18px; align-items: flex-start;">
							<span class="risk-sev ptag ptag-pain" style="flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 3px;">High</span>
							<div class="risk-content">
								<h4>Tenant cancels the tenancy before the moving cost is fully repaid</h4>
								<p>This is the central credit risk of the installment model. If a tenant opts in, Rendin pays the mover €200 upfront, but the tenant leaves at month 5 — Rendin has collected ~€85 and is owed €115 it may not recover easily. At 95 opt-ins/month, even a 10% early exit rate creates a meaningful exposure. Four mitigations work in combination:</p>
							</div>
						</div>
						<div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 12px;">
							<div class="cs-card" style="padding: 16px 18px;">
								<p style="font-family: 'Trebuchet MS', sans-serif; font-size: 0.68rem; color: var(--accent-strong); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 8px;">Mitigation 1 · Delayed payout</p>
								<p style="font-size: 0.88rem;">Rendin does not pay the mover on day 1. Instead it pays after month 3 or 4, once enough installments have been collected to cover the full cost. The tenant still gets the service immediately — the mover agrees to a 90-day payment term in exchange for guaranteed referral volume.</p>
							</div>
							<div class="cs-card" style="padding: 16px 18px;">
								<p style="font-family: 'Trebuchet MS', sans-serif; font-size: 0.68rem; color: rgba(20,100,60,0.85); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 8px;">Mitigation 2 · Tenancy obligation</p>
								<p style="font-size: 0.88rem;">The outstanding moving balance is written into the Rendin agreement as a financial obligation — treated the same as unpaid rent if the tenant exits early. Rendin already has a recovery mechanism for rent arrears and can apply the same process without building anything new.</p>
							</div>
							<div class="cs-card" style="padding: 16px 18px;">
								<p style="font-family: 'Trebuchet MS', sans-serif; font-size: 0.68rem; color: rgba(20,55,120,0.85); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 8px;">Mitigation 3 · Partial upfront payment</p>
								<p style="font-size: 0.88rem;">Rendin only finances 70% of the move via installments. The tenant pays 30% — roughly €60 on move day — reducing Rendin's exposure from €200 to €140 per tenant. The move-in is still far cheaper than paying the full amount upfront, so the proposition remains compelling.</p>
							</div>
							<div class="cs-card" style="padding: 16px 18px;">
								<p style="font-family: 'Trebuchet MS', sans-serif; font-size: 0.68rem; color: rgba(181,98,10,0.85); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom: 8px;">Mitigation 4 · Insurance backstop</p>
								<p style="font-size: 0.88rem;">Rendin already underwrites rental income risk with ERGO Insurance. The moving installment default risk is structurally similar — a tenant financial obligation that may not be honoured. This could fold into the existing insurance framework, pricing in the default rate at the portfolio level rather than per tenant.</p>
							</div>
						</div>
						<p style="font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--muted);">In practice, Mitigations 1 and 2 together are sufficient for a first version — delayed payout removes the immediate cash risk, and the tenancy obligation gives a legal recovery path. Mitigations 3 and 4 are phase 2 refinements as volume grows.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="risk-item">
						<span class="risk-sev ptag ptag-need">Medium</span>
						<div class="risk-content">
							<h4>Low conversion makes the feature not worth maintaining</h4>
							<p>If fewer than 15% of eligible tenants engage, the economics don't justify the partner management overhead. Set a 3-month pilot with a clear kill threshold. If conversion is below 15% at month 3, run one round of UX testing before deciding to kill or pivot to landlord-side (e.g. "find move-out services").</p>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="risk-item">
						<span class="risk-sev ptag ptag-need">Medium</span>
						<div class="risk-content">
							<h4>Regulatory complexity in Poland</h4>
							<p>Referral arrangements with Polish moving companies may have different tax and commercial law implications. Replicate the Estonia model only after a local legal review. Phase the Poland launch 6 months after Estonia proves conversion.</p>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="risk-item">
						<span class="risk-sev ptag ptag-ctx">Low</span>
						<div class="risk-content">
							<h4>Rendin may already have looked at this</h4>
							<p>There is a real chance Rendin has evaluated and deprioritised this, or has it on a near-term roadmap. This case study is a structured product exercise, not a claim to have found a blind spot. The analysis stands regardless — the gap exists, the model is viable, and the fit is clear.</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>

			<!-- 07 Conclusion -->
			<section class="cs-conclusion">
				<p class="cs-section-num">07 — Conclusion</p>
				<h2>The opportunity<br>in a sentence</h2>
				<p>
					Rendin has a precise intent signal — move-in date, address, verified tenant identity — that no moving company in Estonia or Poland possesses. A lightweight referral feature turns this into a zero-capex revenue stream, a brand-consistent user experience, and a plausible reduction in insurance claims through better-documented, less chaotic move-ins.
				</p>

				<div class="conclusion-grid">
					<div class="conclusion-point">
						<h4>For founders</h4>
						<p>This is an embedded services play. Rendin already owns the trust layer. The moving referral is a wedge into a broader move-in bundle — storage, internet setup, furniture — that could become a real revenue line at scale.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="conclusion-point">
						<h4>For investors</h4>
						<p>The referral model is asset-light with no additional burn. Adding a €40–200k adjacent revenue stream from the same customer base is accretive — and replicates to each new market automatically.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="conclusion-point">
						<h4>For Rendin</h4>
						<p>Whether or not this specific feature ships, the post-signing journey is an underused canvas. A tenant who has a smooth, Rendin-helped move-in is the most likely to leave a five-star review — and eventually become a landlord on the platform.</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<p class="cs-disclaimer">
					Independent product case study prepared for portfolio purposes. All figures are estimated from publicly available data. Rendin's actual roadmap or internal evaluation of this opportunity is not known to the author.
				</p>
			</section>

